00:26:01,619 --> 00:26:03,700
Did you, Follan, did you hear that?

498
00:26:03,700 --> 00:26:05,059
Yeah, I thought I heard something.

499
00:26:05,059 --> 00:26:05,860
Is everything okay?

500
00:26:06,980 --> 00:26:08,019
I don't know.

501
00:26:08,019 --> 00:26:09,140
I don't feel like...

502
00:26:11,380 --> 00:26:13,620
A danger situation, you know?

503
00:26:13,620 --> 00:26:14,259
Agreed.

504
00:26:14,259 --> 00:26:16,340
I just don't love an unearthly voice.

505
00:26:16,340 --> 00:26:17,620
It doesn't like...

506
00:26:17,620 --> 00:26:21,940
Yeah, I don't really have enough information to base things off yet.

507
00:26:21,940 --> 00:26:26,819
In a weirdly specific note, just randomly in the forest?

508
00:26:26,819 --> 00:26:27,860
In the forest.

509
00:26:27,860 --> 00:26:28,660
Yeah.

510
00:26:28,740 --> 00:26:34,259
Look down the half-trodden path where the page rustled from,

511
00:26:34,980 --> 00:26:42,100
and you think you hear more like rustling of paper somewhere up ahead.

512
00:26:43,620 --> 00:26:44,420
Oh my god.

513
00:26:46,900 --> 00:26:47,400
What...

514
00:26:49,460 --> 00:26:52,900
What's the chance that this belongs to...

515
00:26:53,620 --> 00:26:54,340
What's his name?

516
00:26:54,980 --> 00:26:55,300
Alastair?

517
00:26:55,300 --> 00:26:56,019
Alastair?

518
00:26:56,019 --> 00:26:56,900
Alastair?

519
00:26:56,900 --> 00:26:57,380
And he's like...

520
00:26:57,380 --> 00:26:58,420
Oh, he probably...

521
00:26:58,420 --> 00:27:01,060
Up there sleeping, and this is paper that's blown out of all this stuff.

522
00:27:01,060 --> 00:27:02,420
Or on his way into town.

523
00:27:02,420 --> 00:27:03,380
He came this way.

524
00:27:03,380 --> 00:27:05,860
We should maybe go look, because he had all that...

525
00:27:06,420 --> 00:27:09,860
You know, he was carrying that huge satchel with all those papers.

526
00:27:09,860 --> 00:27:11,060
Maybe it's important.

527
00:27:11,060 --> 00:27:12,820
Maybe he's up there, like you said.

528
00:27:13,940 --> 00:27:15,140
I mean, we should go look, right?

529
00:27:18,020 --> 00:27:21,220
Gentlemen, we're gonna go this way,

530
00:27:21,220 --> 00:27:27,220
because part of adventuring is following a strange clue.

531
00:27:27,620 --> 00:27:29,140
We call them side quests.

532
00:27:29,140 --> 00:27:32,980
Did I ever tell you about the time I parried a lightning bolt?

533
00:27:32,980 --> 00:27:34,260
Tell us all about it.

534
00:27:34,260 --> 00:27:34,980
As we walk this way.

535
00:27:34,980 --> 00:27:36,420
And then I speed walk away.

536
00:27:36,420 --> 00:27:39,860
Steel blade to raw magic, I tell you.

537
00:27:39,860 --> 00:27:42,180
The sparks were something to behold.

538
00:27:43,540 --> 00:27:45,140
So you quickly walk ahead.

539
00:27:45,140 --> 00:27:45,640
Yeah.

540
00:27:46,260 --> 00:27:49,380
You don't have to walk for very long, just a few minutes,

541
00:27:49,380 --> 00:27:52,100
and the paper rustling sound gets louder.

542
00:27:52,820 --> 00:27:56,260
And you cut through this cove of trees,

543
00:27:56,259 --> 00:28:01,379
and you stumble upon what looks like an abandoned camp.

544
00:28:01,379 --> 00:28:03,299
A fire that has long since been put out.

545
00:28:03,299 --> 00:28:04,660
No smoke or anything.

546
00:28:04,660 --> 00:28:05,859
Not hot to the touch.

547
00:28:05,859 --> 00:28:08,980
Looks like a couple turned over bedrolls.

548
00:28:10,099 --> 00:28:18,019
But what really stands out is fluttering up in the trees surrounding this camp

549
00:28:19,619 --> 00:28:23,140
are pages that look like they've been torn from a journal.

550
00:28:23,859 --> 00:28:25,379
Cav, can you reach those?

551
00:28:25,380 --> 00:28:25,940
I can't.

552
00:28:26,580 --> 00:28:28,900
I mean, I can get some of these ones, but.

553
00:28:28,900 --> 00:28:30,020
I want to climb a tree.

554
00:28:31,700 --> 00:28:32,500
All right.

555
00:28:32,500 --> 00:28:34,580
As not child children do.

556
00:28:34,580 --> 00:28:35,080
Yeah.

557
00:28:35,620 --> 00:28:39,780
Roll athletics or acrobatics with advantage because you're a child.

558
00:28:40,740 --> 00:28:41,060
Yeah.

559
00:28:41,060 --> 00:28:44,020
And I'll be trying to gather anything lower down.

560
00:28:44,020 --> 00:28:44,520
Sure.

561
00:28:45,060 --> 00:28:47,060
I'll acrobat this.

562
00:28:47,060 --> 00:28:50,260
That's a 13, and that's an 8.

563
00:28:50,260 --> 00:28:50,760
13!

564
00:28:51,780 --> 00:28:53,300
Your foot slips a little bit at first,

565
00:28:53,300 --> 00:28:54,980
but you are able to climb the trees.

566
00:28:55,779 --> 00:28:57,299
It's not elegant is what you're.

567
00:28:57,299 --> 00:28:58,339
No, it's not.

568
00:28:58,339 --> 00:29:02,019
It's not as quick and nimble as you were kind of making it out to be.

569
00:29:03,059 --> 00:29:05,299
Maybe it's a little mossier than you thought.

570
00:29:05,299 --> 00:29:06,180
It was going to look really cool.

571
00:29:06,180 --> 00:29:06,900
Exactly.

572
00:29:06,900 --> 00:29:07,400
Yeah.

573
00:29:07,940 --> 00:29:10,420
You do have a little slip, but as you're getting up,

574
00:29:10,420 --> 00:29:13,539
you can reach a number of the pages at the very least.

575
00:29:14,259 --> 00:29:17,539
Everybody's kind of collecting them and bringing them back around.

576
00:29:17,539 --> 00:29:24,099
And you look down at the pages and everybody roll a d20 just for the first

577
00:29:24,100 --> 00:29:24,980
thing that you see.

578
00:29:25,780 --> 00:29:26,420
God damn it.

579
00:29:26,420 --> 00:29:26,660
Three.

580
00:29:26,660 --> 00:29:27,380
Six.

581
00:29:27,380 --> 00:29:27,940
Nineteen.

582
00:29:28,660 --> 00:29:31,540
Oh, I thought we were going to have like a three, six, nine,

583
00:29:31,540 --> 00:29:33,940
but then he said teen, and I was blown away.

584
00:29:35,860 --> 00:29:37,380
Did the dice go that high?

585
00:29:37,380 --> 00:29:40,180
I didn't even know that those numbers were on there.

586
00:29:40,180 --> 00:29:41,140
Sorry, I couldn't help it.

587
00:29:42,020 --> 00:29:43,940
Never seen 19 before in my life.

588
00:29:44,980 --> 00:29:45,460
OK.

589
00:29:45,460 --> 00:29:47,060
I've been rolling a d10 this whole time.

590
00:29:49,140 --> 00:29:49,940
I have a question.

591
00:29:49,940 --> 00:29:53,460
Depending on what you roll, the higher up you roll,

592
00:29:53,460 --> 00:29:57,460
is it like the more information that you get from what we're looking at?

593
00:29:58,579 --> 00:29:59,860
Or is it just random?

594
00:30:01,220 --> 00:30:04,900
I have them bucketed into different types of information,

595
00:30:04,900 --> 00:30:09,860
but no one is more important than the other at this point, perceptively.

596
00:30:09,860 --> 00:30:10,100
OK.

597
00:30:10,100 --> 00:30:10,740
What do you guys...

598
00:30:11,940 --> 00:30:14,180
Is the writing all the same for us?

599
00:30:14,180 --> 00:30:17,220
Like, and do we recognize it as...

600
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:19,779
Alastair's?

601
00:30:19,779 --> 00:30:20,259
Alastair.

602
00:30:20,259 --> 00:30:21,620
I keep wanting to call him the Sandville.

603
00:30:21,620 --> 00:30:22,579
I don't know why.

604
00:30:23,059 --> 00:30:24,179
That was Cthulhu, Carla.

605
00:30:24,179 --> 00:30:25,139
That was Cthulhu.

606
00:30:25,139 --> 00:30:25,939
I know.

607
00:30:25,939 --> 00:30:29,059
From, yeah, from, I mean, he had lots of journals

608
00:30:29,059 --> 00:30:31,379
and was scrawling things down as he was talking to you.

609
00:30:31,379 --> 00:30:33,059
It doesn't look like his writing.

610
00:30:33,059 --> 00:30:33,699
OK.

611
00:30:33,699 --> 00:30:36,419
There are some similarities between some of the pages,

612
00:30:36,419 --> 00:30:40,419
but it doesn't look like it is one person's journal.

613
00:30:41,059 --> 00:30:41,559
OK.

614
00:30:42,339 --> 00:30:45,379
Well, this one, I feel like Kav, you're going to be interested in this.

615
00:30:45,379 --> 00:30:46,099
Listen to this.

616
00:30:46,099 --> 00:30:46,980
Oh, OK.

617
00:30:47,059 --> 00:30:51,059
Kingstown's first scribes chained their souls here,

618
00:30:51,059 --> 00:30:52,900
so Wintersmith might endure.

619
00:30:53,700 --> 00:30:54,579
You know anything about that?

620
00:30:54,579 --> 00:30:55,299
You're from the city.

621
00:30:56,900 --> 00:30:57,539
No.

622
00:30:57,539 --> 00:31:00,740
As you say that, that wind pipes up again.

623
00:31:02,180 --> 00:31:06,420
If you burn the book, it only writes itself again than you.

624
00:31:11,620 --> 00:31:14,660
Did anyone else feel like it kind of cut off halfway through?

625
00:31:15,460 --> 00:31:15,940
Yeah.

626
00:31:15,940 --> 00:31:18,740
Or in you, like in your body.

627
00:31:18,740 --> 00:31:19,220
Yeah.

628
00:31:19,220 --> 00:31:20,259
What did that mean?

629
00:31:21,140 --> 00:31:26,180
Folan's like, yeah, that didn't sound great.

630
00:31:26,180 --> 00:31:28,180
Do they have a fire pit?

631
00:31:28,180 --> 00:31:29,940
I assume they can.

632
00:31:29,940 --> 00:31:33,700
Yeah, yeah, it looks like it's long since been put out,

633
00:31:33,700 --> 00:31:37,140
but it looks like there was a fire pit, whoever used this last.

634
00:31:37,140 --> 00:31:43,700
When I look around there, I want to look to see if they've tried to burn pages.

635
00:31:44,180 --> 00:31:45,059
Pages.

636
00:31:45,059 --> 00:31:47,380
Yeah, there's no danger or anything.

637
00:31:47,380 --> 00:31:54,740
You kind of sift through the soot, and there are bits of paper in there.

638
00:31:56,100 --> 00:31:58,740
Long since blackened, some have kind of blown away.

639
00:32:00,420 --> 00:32:06,019
Nothing really remaining that you could connect to the pages

640
00:32:06,019 --> 00:32:07,620
that you're seeing that you've pulled from the trees.

641
00:32:08,340 --> 00:32:09,539
What does your stake have?

642
00:32:10,180 --> 00:32:14,099
Its shelves were carved from the bones of Oathbreakers.

643
00:32:15,059 --> 00:32:15,700
You are late.

644
00:32:16,579 --> 00:32:18,819
The archive already opened.

645
00:32:18,819 --> 00:32:19,539
You are late.

646
00:32:21,059 --> 00:32:23,059
Does anyone else get the feeling like we're late?

647
00:32:24,259 --> 00:32:28,259
Well, does that mean like did Alistair find the archive?

648
00:32:29,379 --> 00:32:31,059
Dude was like just asleep.

649
00:32:32,019 --> 00:32:33,299
Like just today?

650
00:32:33,299 --> 00:32:33,799
Yeah.

651
00:32:34,980 --> 00:32:36,339
I saw him on a bench.

652
00:32:36,980 --> 00:32:39,860
Wait, do you think the archive was inside him all along?

653
00:32:40,820 --> 00:32:47,140
Well, I don't, this piece of paper says he will walk these halls again,

654
00:32:47,940 --> 00:32:52,180
though ink has claimed his tongue.

655
00:32:53,140 --> 00:32:55,700
They chained me in the margins.

656
00:32:55,700 --> 00:32:58,260
I can still hear them turning the page.

657
00:32:59,940 --> 00:33:01,220
Someone's stuck in a book.

658
00:33:02,020 --> 00:33:03,300
It sure seems that way.

659
00:33:03,300 --> 00:33:04,180
It does seem that way.

660
00:33:04,180 --> 00:33:05,540
Can you get trapped in a book?

661
00:33:06,180 --> 00:33:08,579
Ethereal voice, are you a good guy or a bad guy?

662
00:33:09,460 --> 00:33:10,659
Legally, you have to tell us.

663
00:33:11,940 --> 00:33:12,740
It's worth a shot.

664
00:33:12,740 --> 00:33:13,619
That's what June says.

665
00:33:14,579 --> 00:33:15,859
No response.

666
00:33:15,859 --> 00:33:18,899
But as you're kind of pausing and looking around,

667
00:33:19,700 --> 00:33:25,619
everybody in the group of gentlemen with you is like stone still,

668
00:33:25,619 --> 00:33:29,460
even though they have weapons piling up all around them.

669
00:33:29,460 --> 00:33:32,899
And as you kind of relax just a moment,

670
00:33:32,900 --> 00:33:36,580
you hear something move in the trees behind you.

671
00:33:36,580 --> 00:33:37,780
You all turn and look,

672
00:33:37,780 --> 00:33:41,380
and you feel like you see an animal disappear off into the forest.

673
00:33:43,300 --> 00:33:46,180
Oh, was that, did you guys see that?

674
00:33:46,180 --> 00:33:47,060
Was that the ghost elk?

675
00:33:48,340 --> 00:33:49,380
I don't know.

676
00:33:49,380 --> 00:33:51,940
I just saw like rustling, like something moved over there, though.

677
00:33:52,900 --> 00:33:59,060
Perhaps we, do we want to take these pages or leave these pages and perhaps?

678
00:33:59,060 --> 00:34:00,180
I'll take them.

679
00:34:00,180 --> 00:34:01,540
I think we should definitely take them.

680
00:34:01,539 --> 00:34:03,940
We can't just leave all this litter in the forest.

681
00:34:03,940 --> 00:34:07,220
No, no, you're supposed to leave no trace.

682
00:34:07,220 --> 00:34:11,699
Leave this space and go see if we can't find that elk.

683
00:34:11,699 --> 00:34:14,099
And Merrick heads off into the woods.

684
00:34:14,099 --> 00:34:14,820
Stupid!

685
00:34:14,820 --> 00:34:15,619
He's nervous.

686
00:34:15,619 --> 00:34:16,340
I get it.

687
00:34:16,340 --> 00:34:17,219
I fold the pages.

688
00:34:17,219 --> 00:34:18,259
I put them in my bucket.

